Boil a #large pot{} of @water{to taste}(salted) for the @dried rigatoni{180%grams}.

When boiling, add the rigatoni to the water and bring back to the boil. Cook until softened, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the #pot{}, off the heat. Drizzle with @oil{to taste} and stir through to prevent sticking.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic{1}(grated) (or use a garlic press). Halve, peel and thinly slice the @shallot{1}(thinly sliced).

Place a #large pan{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}. Once hot, add the @diced Irish chicken breast{260%grams} and shallot. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands after handling raw chicken.

Fry until chicken is browned on the outside, ~{3-4%mins}. Add the garlic and @Cajun spice mix{2%sachets}. Cook, stirring, ~{1%min}.

> TIP: Notice a stronger smell from your chicken? Don't worry, this is normal due to packaging we use to keep it fresh.

Add @water{100%ml}, @sugar{½%tsp}, @passata{1%pack} and @chicken stock{1%sachet} to the #pan{}. Bring to the boil then reduce the heat. Simmer until the chicken is cooked through, ~{10-12%mins}.

> IMPORTANT: Chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once the sauce has thickened slightly, add the @baby spinach{120%grams} a handful at a time, stirring until wilted.

Stir through the @creme fraiche{110%grams} and a knob of @butter{to taste}. Bring to the boil then remove from the heat. Season the sauce to taste with salt, pepper and sugar.

Add the drained pasta to the creamy sauce and toss to combine. Divide your Cajun chicken pasta between #bowls{2}. Finish with a sprinkling of @grated Italian style hard cheese{25%grams}.